<DOC><DOCNO> AP890921-0202 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2149EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-21 0489</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</SECOND><HEAD>Hurricane Hugo Bears Down on Southeast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Hurricane Hugo, packing 135 mph winds, headed for the mainlandUnited States on Thursday, bringing showers to much of the Southeastand prompting a hurricane warning from Florida to North Carolina.   Elsewhere around the nation, showers and thunderstorms werewidely scattered from the central Gulf Coast states through thelower Ohio Valley to the middle Atlantic Coast states and southernNew England.   A hurricane warning was in effect from Fernandina Beach, Fla., tothe Oregon inlet of North Carolina, including Pamlico Sound, with atropical storm warning and hurricane watch in effect from the oregoninlet to Cape Henlopen, N.C., including the Albermarle Sound andChesapeake Bay.   High wind warnings were in effect through Friday for the northand south Midlands of South Carolina and south central sections ofVirginia.   Storm surge flooding 12 to 17 feet above normal tide levels wasexpected near and to the north of where the center of the hurricanecrosses the coast.   A few tornadoes were likely in parts of South Carolina and NorthCarolina, with rainfall amounts of 5 to 10 inches expected in thepath of the hurricane.   Flash flood watches issued for South Carolina, North Carolina andsoutheastern Georgia. Flash flood watches were posted for Friday forVirginia, Maryland, Delaware, the eastern Panhandle of WestVirginia, and the District of Columbia.   A coastal flood watch issued for Friday in much of the middleAtlantic Coast. An urban and small stream flood watch was postedthrough Friday evening for the lower Susquehanna Valley ofPennsylvania.   Showers and thunderstorms associated with Hugo were in SouthCarolina, eastern Georgia and coastal North Carolina.   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hours ending at 8 p.m. EDTincluded 1{ inches at Savannah, Ga. 1 1-3 inches at Fort Stewart,Ga., and nine-tenths of an inch at Beaufort, S.C.   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended across eastern Nebraskaand central Kansas, as well as the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas.   Cloudy skies and a few showers prevailed over the north centralUnited States, with fair skies predominant across the western thirdof the country.   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed across Florida, with hightemperatures in the lower 90s at many locations. Miami Beach's93-degree high was a record for the date.   Afternoon highs were mostly in the 80s across southeastern andsouth central sections of the country, with readings in the 90sreported in southern Texas and in the 80s and 90s in thesouthwestern deserts.   Clouds and rain helped keep temperatures unseasonably cool in thenorth central United States, with afternoon readings only in the 50sfrom northern Minnesota to the central High Plains.   An arctic cold front with strong northwest winds is expected tobring much colder weather to the north central states in time forthe official start of autumn Friday evening, with freezingtemperatures expected by Saturday morning.</TEXT></DOC>